# We see here that 3 features in the dataset are missing substantial amount of the data. 
# We have to deal with all the missing values in different way.
# We have replaced director and cast with NA whereas in case of Country, we can use MODE but here we are missing lot of values,
#         hence I just droped all the missing values in 'Other' bucket just to get better graph.


disney['director'].replace(np.nan, 'NA',inplace  = True)
disney['cast'].replace(np.nan, 'NA',inplace  = True)
disney['country'].replace(np.nan, 'Other',inplace  = True)

# disney['country'] = disney['country'].fillna(disney['country'].mode()[0])

disney.drop_duplicates(inplace= True)

In [18]:
# Quick feature engineering

# Helper column for various plots
disney['count'] = 1

# Many productions have several countries listed - this will skew our results , we'll grab the first one mentioned

# Lets retrieve just the first country
disney['first_country'] = disney['country'].apply(lambda x: x.split(",")[0])
disney['first_country'].head()

# Rating ages from this notebook: https://www.kaggle.com/andreshg/eda-beginner-to-expert-plotly (thank you!)

ratings_ages = {
    'TV-PG': 'Older Kids',
    'TV-Y7-FV': 'Older Kids',
    'TV-Y7': 'Older Kids',
    'TV-14': 'Teens',
    'TV-Y': 'Kids',
    'PG-13': 'Teens',
    'TV-G': 'Kids',
    'PG': 'Older Kids',
    'G': 'Kids',
    
#     'TV-MA': 'Adults',
#     'R': 'Adults',
#     'NR': 'Adults',
#     'UR': 'Adults',
#     'NC-17': 'Adults',
#     '13+':'Teens',
#     '16+':'Teens',
#     '18+':'Adults',
#     '7+':'Older Kids',
#     'TV-NR':'Adults',
#     '16':'Teens',
#     'AGES_16_':'Teens',
#     'AGES_18_':'Adults'
            
}

disney['target_ages'] = disney['rating'].replace(ratings_ages)
disney['target_ages'].unique()

# Genre

disney['genre'] = disney['listed_in'].apply(lambda x :  x.replace(' ,',',').replace(', ',',').split(',')) 

# Reducing name length

disney['first_country'].replace('United States', 'USA', inplace=True)
disney['first_country'].replace('United Kingdom', 'UK',inplace=True)
disney['first_country'].replace('South Korea', 'S. Korea',inplace=True)

country_order = disney['first_country'].value_counts()[:11].index

data_q2q3['sum'] = data_q2q3.sum(axis=1)
data_q2q3_ratio = (data_q2q3.T / data_q2q3['sum']).T[['Movie', 'TV Show']].sort_values(by='Movie',ascending=False)[::-1]

data_q2q3_ratio['Movie'] = data_q2q3_ratio['Movie'].fillna(0)

ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)
plt.axis('off')

# Constants = parameters controling the plot layout:
upperLimit = 30
lowerLimit = 1
labelPadding = 30

# Compute max and min in the dataset
max = disney_polar['Value'].max()

# Let's compute heights: they are a conversion of each item value in those new coordinates
# In our example, 0 in the dataset will be converted to the lowerLimit (10)
# The maximum will be converted to the upperLimit (100)
slope = (max - lowerLimit) / max
heights = slope * disney_polar.Value + lowerLimit

# Compute the width of each bar. In total we have 2*Pi = 360
width = 2*np.pi / len(disney_polar.index)

# Compute the angle each bar is centered on:
indexes = list(range(1, len(disney_polar.index)+1))
angles = [element * width for element in indexes]
angles

# Draw bars
bars = ax.bar(
    x=angles, 
    height=heights, 
    width=width, 
    bottom=lowerLimit,
    linewidth=2, 
    edgecolor="white",
    color=color_map,alpha=0.8
)

# Add labels
for bar, angle, height, label in zip(bars,angles, heights, disney_polar["month_name_added"]):

    # Labels are rotated. Rotation must be specified in degrees :(
    rotation = np.rad2deg(angle)

    # Flip some labels upside down
    alignment = ""
    if angle >= np.pi/2 and angle < 3*np.pi/2:
        alignment = "right"
        rotation = rotation + 180
    else: 
        alignment = "left"

    # Finally add the labels
    ax.text(
        x=angle, 
        y=lowerLimit + bar.get_height() + labelPadding, 
        s=label, 
        ha=alignment, fontsize=10,fontfamily='serif',
        va='center', 
        rotation=rotation, 
        rotation_mode="anchor")

# Genres
from sklearn.preprocessing import MultiLabelBinarizer 

import matplotlib.colors


# Custom colour map based on Netflix palette
cmap = matplotlib.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("", ['#221f1f', '#b20710','#f5f5f1'])



def genre_heatmap(df, title):
    disney['genre'] = disney['listed_in'].apply(lambda x :  x.replace(' ,',',').replace(', ',',').split(',')) 
    Types = []
    for i in disney['genre']: Types += i
    Types = set(Types)
    print("There are {} types in the Netflix {} Dataset".format(len(Types),title))    
    test = disney['genre']
    mlb = MultiLabelBinarizer()
    res = pd.DataFrame(mlb.fit_transform(test), columns=mlb.classes_, index=test.index)
    corr = res.corr()
    mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
    mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 7))
    fig.text(.54,.88,'Genre correlation', fontfamily='serif',fontweight='bold',fontsize=15)
    fig.text(.75,.665,
            '''
             It is interesting that Independant Movies
             tend to be Dramas. 
             
             Another observation is that 
             Internatinal Movies are rarely
             in the Children's genre.
             ''', fontfamily='serif',fontsize=12,ha='right')
    pl = sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=.3, vmin=-.3, center=0, square=True, linewidths=2.5)
    
    plt.show()
